################################################################################
  SECTION 1: PREMIUM LIGHT MODE APP EXAMPLES (2025-2026)
################################################################################

  The difference between a premium light mode and a generic one is deliberate
  craft. As Nathan Curtis (EightShapes) writes: "To be excellent, you have to
  handcraft that stuff." Direct translation from dark to light -- or worse,
  defaulting to #FFFFFF and calling it done -- produces mediocre results. Every
  premium app that nails light mode shares common traits: tinted backgrounds,
  brand-consistent accents, purple/blue-tinted shadows, and typography that
  breathes.

  1.1 THINGS 3 (Cultured Code, Stuttgart)
  ----------------------------------------

    Two Apple Design Awards. The gold standard for premium light mode in
    productivity apps. When you open a task, it "smoothly transforms into a
    clear white piece of paper, ready for your thoughts" -- minimal, distraction-
    free, almost tactile. Things 3 offers three appearances: light, dark, and
    pure black (OLED).

    What makes it premium:
    - Background is NOT #FFFFFF -- it is a warm off-white with extremely subtle
      blue-gray undertones (approximately #FAFAFA with a cool tint)
    - Cards have almost no visible border -- depth comes from extremely subtle
      shadows with low opacity (< 5%)
    - Typography uses carefully weighted text -- headings are medium weight
      (not bold), creating an airy, editorial feel
    - Color is used sparingly -- project dots, due dates, priority flags
    - The completion animation is a satisfying checkbox fill with haptic
      feedback, no confetti, no excess
    - Every interaction feels intentional: drag-and-drop is fluid, with items
      morphing shape as they move between sections

    Key takeaway for UNJYNX: Restraint IS luxury. Fewer colors on screen,
    more white space, subtle depth. On light mode, less is always more.


  1.2 LINEAR (Linear Software, San Francisco)
  --------------------------------------------

    Linear rebuilt its entire color system using LCH (Lightness, Chroma, Hue)
    color space instead of HSL. This ensures perpetually uniform color
    appearance -- making it possible to generate consistently good-looking
    themes regardless of base colors. Instead of defining 98 specific
    variables per theme, they simplified to three: base color, accent color,
    and contrast.

    What makes it premium:
    - Background uses a light neutral with extremely subtle warmth (~#FAFAF9)
    - Light mode improvements specifically "increased overall contrast and
      returned to a more neutral and timeless appearance"
    - Text and neutral icons made DARKER in light mode (not lighter -- this
      is counterintuitive but critical for readability)
    - Uses Inter Display for headings (more expression) and regular Inter
      for body text
    - Custom theme generator allows users to personalize light mode while
      maintaining accessibility through LCH-based generation
    - The sidebar uses a slightly tinted surface (not same-white as content)
      to create architectural hierarchy

    Key takeaway for UNJYNX: Use perceptually uniform color space (LCH/OKLCH)
    for generating tonal palettes. Ensure light mode text is DARKER than you
    think it needs to be. Create hierarchy through surface tinting, not just
    shadows.


  1.3 ARC BROWSER (The Browser Company, New York)
  -------------------------------------------------

    Won the 2025 Red Dot Design Award for Interface Design. Arc's light mode
    features Adaptive Color Schemes that automatically adjust to complement the
    website being viewed. The UI is minimalist, with drag-and-drop convenience,
    pinning, and archiving -- all without visual chaos.

    What makes it premium:
    - Color schemes are context-aware -- the browser chrome subtly adapts to the
      page content, making light mode feel alive rather than static
    - Sidebar uses a distinct tinted surface (slightly cooler than content area)
    - Typography is clean, with generous spacing between navigation elements
    - Gesture controls add a layer of polish that makes the UI feel premium
      without visual clutter

    Key takeaway for UNJYNX: Consider context-aware tinting in light mode --
    different screens could have very subtle surface variations that make the
    experience feel organic and intentional rather than a single flat color.


  1.4 CRAFT (Craft Docs, Budapest)
  ----------------------------------

    Craft is "built for digital devices" -- beautiful document creation with
    aesthetically linked pages. The light mode is its default state, and it
    feels like luxury stationery brought to life.

    What makes it premium:
    - The background is a warm off-white that evokes high-quality paper
    - Document cards have subtle rounded corners with barely-visible shadows
    - The typography is serif-forward for content, creating an editorial feel
    - Transitions between views are smooth with slight parallax depth
    - Color palette is muted -- pastels for tags, with most UI chrome in
      neutral tones

    Key takeaway for UNJYNX: The "luxury stationery" metaphor works well for
    productivity apps in light mode. #F8F5FF achieves this -- it feels like
    premium paper with a purple warmth.


  1.5 AMIE (Amie.so, Berlin)
  ----------------------------

    Described as "what you'd get if a fashion brand created a calendar app."
    The most beautiful calendar on the market. Uses minimal pastel colors with
    quirky, delightful micro-interactions.

    What makes it premium:
    - The light mode uses a warm off-white that feels distinctly NOT generic
    - Calendar events use pastel fills (not saturated colors) that work
      harmoniously on the light background
    - Navigation transitions are fluid with subtle spring physics
    - The todo integration feels seamless -- tasks slide into calendar with
      smooth morphing animations
    - Every UI element has generous padding and whitespace

    Key takeaway for UNJYNX: Pastel versions of brand colors work better on
    light backgrounds than saturated ones. Calendar/time views should use
    lighter tints of brand colors (lavender instead of violet, gold wash
    instead of bright gold).


  1.6 NOTION (Notion Labs, San Francisco)
  -----------------------------------------

    While Notion's light mode is clean, it is NOT the best example of premium
    light mode. Notion uses a slightly warm gray background (~#FFFFFF with
    warm undertones on some surfaces), but the overall feel is more functional
    than luxurious.

    What they get right:
    - Consistent spacing system (8px grid)
    - Clean typography hierarchy
    - Subtle hover states on blocks

    What they get wrong (for our purposes):
    - Too close to pure white -- lacks brand identity in light mode
    - Dark mode feels more intentionally designed than light mode
    - Light mode can feel clinical rather than warm

    Key takeaway for UNJYNX: Our #F8F5FF already differentiates us from
    Notion's near-white approach. The purple tint IS our light mode brand
    identity.


