################################################################################
  SECTION 2: APPLE LIQUID GLASS + LIGHT MODE
################################################################################

  Apple introduced Liquid Glass at WWDC 2025 as a system-wide design material
  across iOS 26, iPadOS 26, macOS Tahoe, watchOS 26, and tvOS 26. It is
  described as "a translucent material that reflects and refracts its
  surroundings, while dynamically transforming to help bring greater focus to
  content."

  2.1 HOW LIQUID GLASS WORKS ON LIGHT BACKGROUNDS
  -------------------------------------------------

    In light mode, Liquid Glass "blends in, sometimes a bit too much" -- this
    is the central challenge. On dark backgrounds, glass elements pop with
    specular highlights against the contrast. On light backgrounds, the glass
    material needs more defined edges and slightly higher opacity to maintain
    visibility.

    Light Mode Liquid Glass Properties:
    - Higher base opacity than dark mode (60-80% vs 40-60%)
    - Less dramatic blur (6-10px sigma vs 10-20px sigma)
    - Relies more on subtle BORDERS than on background contrast
    - Specular highlights shift from bright white to subtle warm tones
    - The material adapts automatically between Light and Dark Mode

    Critical Rule from Apple: "Liquid Glass is exclusively for the navigation
    layer that floats above app content. Never apply to content itself
    (lists, tables, media)."

  2.2 FLUTTER IMPLEMENTATION OF LIQUID GLASS
  --------------------------------------------

    Multiple approaches exist as of early 2026:

    A) BackdropFilter (Built-in Flutter):
       The most straightforward approach. Uses BackdropFilter + ImageFilter.blur
       to create real-time Gaussian blur entirely in Dart.

       LIGHT MODE PARAMETERS:

       BackdropFilter(
         filter: ImageFilter.blur(sigmaX: 8.0, sigmaY: 8.0),
         child: Container(
           decoration: BoxDecoration(
             color: Color(0xBFF8F5FF),  // 75% opacity purple mist
             borderRadius: BorderRadius.circular(16),
             border: Border.all(
               color: Color(0x30FFFFFF),  // 19% white border
               width: 1.0,
             ),
             boxShadow: [
               BoxShadow(
                 color: Color(0x141A0533), // 8% purple shadow
                 blurRadius: 12,
                 offset: Offset(0, 4),
               ),
             ],
           ),
           child: content,
         ),
       )

    B) Available Flutter Packages (pub.dev):
       - liquid_glass_renderer -- advanced lens effects with distortion,
         magnification, refraction, and blur
       - liquid_glass_easy -- real-time liquid glass lens effects
       - glassmorphism -- basic glass effects (older, but stable)

    C) Performance Considerations:
       - Keep blur sigma between 5-15 (higher causes lag)
       - Use RepaintBoundary to isolate blur from widget tree
       - Clip with ClipRRect to limit repaint area
       - On older devices, provide fallback: increased opacity + no blur
       - Use custom RenderObjects for frequently-updating glass effects

  2.3 LIGHT MODE GLASS CARD SPECIFICATION FOR UNJYNX
  ----------------------------------------------------

    UNJYNX should use glass selectively -- NOT on every surface, but on:
    - Bottom navigation bar (floating above content)
    - Top app bar (when scrolled, content passes beneath)
    - Modal bottom sheets
    - Quick-add task overlay
    - NOT on task cards (these need solid backgrounds for readability)

    GLASS CARD TOKENS (LIGHT MODE):

    Property          | Light Mode Value
    ------------------|------------------------------
    Background color  | #F8F5FF at 75% opacity
    Blur sigma        | 8.0 (sigmaX and sigmaY)
    Border            | 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.3)
    Shadow            | rgba(26,5,51,0.08), 12px, y:4
    Border radius     | 16px (xl token)
    Min contrast      | 4.5:1 for text over glass
    Fallback          | #F8F5FF solid at 95% opacity

    COMPARISON TO DARK MODE GLASS:

    Property          | Dark Mode Value
    ------------------|------------------------------
    Background color  | #1A0533 at 50% opacity
    Blur sigma        | 12.0 (sigmaX and sigmaY)
    Border            | 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.1)
    Shadow            | rgba(0,0,0,0.25), 16px, y:6
    Border radius     | 16px (xl token)
    Min contrast      | 4.5:1 for text over glass
    Fallback          | #1A0533 solid at 90% opacity


################################################################################
  SECTION 3: COLOR SCIENCE FOR LIGHT THEMES
################################################################################

  3.1 WHY #F8F5FF WORKS BETTER THAN #FFFFFF
  -------------------------------------------

    Scientific Basis:
    Pure white (#FFFFFF) has 100% luminance. When paired with dark text, the
    extreme contrast (21:1 for pure black) creates "halation" -- a perceived
    glow around dark letterforms that increases visual fatigue during extended
    reading. Research published in IOVS (Investigative Ophthalmology & Visual
    Science) found that reading black text on white for 60 minutes caused
    choroidal thinning in all subjects, potentially contributing to myopia
    development.

    #F8F5FF has a relative luminance of approximately 0.93 (vs 1.0 for white).
    This 7% reduction in luminance:
    - Reduces halation around dark text
    - Decreases the pupil constriction/dilation cycle that causes fatigue
    - Creates a warmer, more inviting reading environment
    - Maintains excellent contrast (18.5:1 with #1A0533 text -- far above
      WCAG AAA's 7:1 requirement)

    Perception Science:
    The subtle purple tint in #F8F5FF (R:248, G:245, B:255 -- note B is highest)
    triggers a subconscious association with premium/luxury brands. Purple is
    historically the color of royalty and sophistication. Users "won't know why
    it feels different, but they'll feel it" -- this is the Mere Exposure Effect
    combined with color-emotion association.

    Industry Precedent:
    - Todoist uses #FEFDFC (warm off-white with yellow-red tint)
    - Apple's default white surfaces are not pure #FFFFFF -- they use
      systemBackground which is a very slightly warm off-white
    - Amazon Kindle's default reading background is #F6F3EB (warm cream)
    - Google Docs uses #FFFFFF for the document but a tinted gray for chrome

  3.2 PURPLE-TINTED SHADOWS VS GRAY SHADOWS
  -------------------------------------------

    Josh W. Comeau's research on designing shadows demonstrates that shadows
    should match the environment they sit in. On a purple-tinted background,
    gray shadows (#000000 at low opacity) look "muddy" and disconnected -- they
    break the color harmony.

    The best way to fix shadows is to change them from black (default) to a
    darker shade of the primary color. Pure black shadows (#000000) look harsh
    and cold. Using very dark purple (our #1A0533) instead creates shadows
    that feel warmer and more natural.

    UNJYNX Shadow System (Light Mode):

    Level | Elevation | Shadow Definition
    ------|-----------|------------------------------------------
    0     | 0dp       | none (page background)
    1     | 1dp       | 0 1px 2px rgba(26,5,51,0.06)
    2     | 3dp       | 0 2px 4px rgba(26,5,51,0.06),
          |           | 0 4px 8px rgba(26,5,51,0.04)
    3     | 6dp       | 0 4px 8px rgba(26,5,51,0.08),
          |           | 0 8px 16px rgba(26,5,51,0.06)
    4     | 8dp       | 0 6px 12px rgba(26,5,51,0.10),
          |           | 0 12px 24px rgba(26,5,51,0.06)
    5     | 12dp      | 0 8px 16px rgba(26,5,51,0.12),
          |           | 0 16px 32px rgba(26,5,51,0.08)

    Key principle: Layered shadows (tight + soft) look more realistic than
    single shadows. The shadow color rgba(26,5,51,alpha) is derived from the
    brand's midnight purple #1A0533 at various opacities. This creates shadows
    that feel native to the purple-tinted environment.

    Flutter Implementation:

      static const purpleShadowColor = Color(0xFF1A0533);

      static List<BoxShadow> elevation2 = [
        BoxShadow(
          color: purpleShadowColor.withOpacity(0.06),
          blurRadius: 4,
          offset: const Offset(0, 2),
        ),
        BoxShadow(
          color: purpleShadowColor.withOpacity(0.04),
          blurRadius: 8,
          offset: const Offset(0, 4),
        ),
      ];

  3.3 GOLD ON LIGHT BACKGROUNDS -- CONTRAST SCIENCE
  ---------------------------------------------------

    The Problem: Standard gold (#FFD700) on white (#FFFFFF) has only 1.4:1
    contrast ratio -- essentially invisible and totally unusable for text or
    interactive elements. Even on #F8F5FF, bright gold achieves roughly 1.5:1.

    The Solution: Dark Goldenrod #B8860B (R:184, G:134, B:11).
    - On #F8F5FF: approximately 4.8:1 contrast ratio (passes WCAG AA)
    - On #FFFFFF: approximately 4.5:1 contrast ratio (barely passes AA)
    - On #EDE5F7 (card surface): approximately 4.3:1 (passes for large text)

    This is why UNJYNX uses TWO gold tokens:
    - Dark mode: #FFD700 (Electric Gold) -- vibrant, high contrast on dark
    - Light mode: #B8860B (Rich Gold) -- deeper, readable on light surfaces

    Additional gold variants for light mode:

    Token           | Hex     | Usage
    ----------------|---------|-------------------------------
    richGold        | #B8860B | CTAs, buttons, active states
    goldWash        | #FFF8E1 | Selected state backgrounds
    goldPressed     | #8B6508 | Pressed/active button state
    goldDisabled    | #D4B896 | Disabled gold elements
    goldBorder      | #C4960F | Focused input borders
    goldShimmer     | #DAA520 | Animation highlight color

  3.4 SEMANTIC COLOR DEEPENING FOR LIGHT BACKGROUNDS
  ----------------------------------------------------

    In dark mode, semantic colors can be vibrant because they sit on a dark
    canvas. In light mode, the same colors become harsh or low-contrast.
    Every semantic color needs a "light mode variant" that is deeper/more
    saturated:

    Semantic  | Dark Mode    | Light Mode   | Reason
    ----------|--------------|--------------|--------------------
    Success   | #10B981      | #059669      | Deeper for contrast
    Warning   | #F59E0B      | #D97706      | Deeper for contrast
    Error     | #F43F5E      | #E11D48      | Deeper for contrast
    Info      | #06B6D4      | #0891B2      | Deeper for contrast
    Gold      | #FFD700      | #B8860B      | 4.8:1 vs 1.4:1
    Text 1    | #F8F5FF      | #1A0533      | Near-maximum
    Text 2    | #C4B5D9      | #6B21A8      | Purple brand tint
    Text 3    | #8B7FA8      | #475569      | Neutral gray
    Border    | #2D1B4E      | #E2D9F3      | Subtle definition

  3.5 PERCEPTUALLY UNIFORM COLOR SPACES (LCH / OKLCH)
  -----------------------------------------------------

    Linear's move to LCH for theme generation is a best practice UNJYNX
    should follow. In HSL, two colors with the same "lightness" value can
    have vastly different PERCEIVED lightness -- a yellow at L:50 looks far
    brighter than a blue at L:50. LCH (Lightness, Chroma, Hue) and its
    improved variant OKLCH solve this:

    - Same L value = same perceived brightness = same contrast ratio
    - Swapping hues at fixed L and C preserves accessibility
    - Adding new palette shades is trivial -- match L and C values
    - Linear reports this simplified their theming from 98 variables to 3

    LCH is described as "the best color space for UI" because it is designed
    to represent colors in a way more similar to how the human eye perceives
    them -- perceptual uniformity. The LCH contrast adjustment algorithm
    generates richer colors while still meeting accessibility requirements,
    whereas HSL darkens colors for accessibility but results in much less
    saturation retention.

    For UNJYNX's light mode tonal palette generation:

    // Generate tonal palette from purple seed using OKLCH
    // L: 0.0 (black) to 1.0 (white)
    // C: 0.0 (gray) to ~0.37 (max chroma)
    // H: 303 (purple hue angle)

    Surface hierarchy (L values):
    background:       L=0.97  -> #F8F5FF (Purple Mist)
    surfaceContainer: L=0.95  -> #F0EAFC (Soft Lavender)
    surfaceElevated:  L=0.93  -> #EDE5F7 (Light Violet)
    surfaceHighest:   L=0.91  -> #E2D9F3 (Medium Lavender)
    surfaceInverse:   L=0.15  -> #1A0533 (Midnight Purple)

    OKLCH is preferred over LCH for better hue consistency in blue/purple
    ranges. CSS supports oklch() natively; in Flutter, use the flex_seed_scheme
    package which provides more control over seed-based color generation
    than Flutter's built-in ColorScheme.fromSeed().


################################################################################
  SECTION 4: LIGHT MODE GLASSMORPHISM
################################################################################

  4.1 THE FUNDAMENTAL CHALLENGE
  ------------------------------

    Glassmorphism on dark backgrounds is visually striking because the glass
    panel contrasts with the dark environment -- translucent white/light
    elements pop against darkness. On light backgrounds, the technique is
    fundamentally different: "technically you can use glassmorphism on solid
    color backgrounds, but visually it's pointless -- you won't see the blur
    since glassmorphism requires variation behind the glass element."

    In 2025, 64% of premium SaaS applications incorporate glassmorphism
    elements, with users reporting 23% higher perceived quality and modernity
    compared to flat design alternatives.

    Solution: Light mode glassmorphism requires CONTENT VARIATION behind the
    glass. Strategies:
    1. Subtle gradient backgrounds (even slight color variation makes blur
       visible)
    2. Content scrolling beneath the glass surface (task list, calendar)
    3. Layered surfaces at different tints creating depth variation
    4. A very faint geometric or organic pattern on the background

  4.2 LIGHT MODE GLASS PARAMETERS
  ---------------------------------

    Light mode glass uses fundamentally different values than dark mode:

    Parameter          | Dark Mode          | Light Mode
    -------------------|--------------------|--------------------------
    Background opacity | 40-60%             | 60-80%
    Blur sigma         | 10-20px            | 6-10px
    Border color       | white at 10-15%    | white at 25-35%
    Border width       | 0.5-1px            | 1px (more definition)
    Shadow color       | black at 20-30%    | purple at 6-12%
    Shadow blur        | 16-24px            | 8-16px
    Specular highlight | bright white edge  | warm white edge
    Content beneath    | Any (high contrast)| Needs variation/color

    The KEY insight: Light mode glass needs STRONGER BORDERS and HIGHER
    OPACITY because the ambient brightness makes the glass panel less
    distinguishable from the background. In dark mode, the glass practically
    draws itself through contrast alone.

  4.3 CSS IMPLEMENTATION (for web admin panel / landing page)
  ------------------------------------------------------------

    .glass-card-light {
      background: rgba(248, 245, 255, 0.75);
      backdrop-filter: blur(8px);
      -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(8px);
      border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.3);
      border-radius: 16px;
      box-shadow:
        0 2px 4px rgba(26, 5, 51, 0.06),
        0 8px 16px rgba(26, 5, 51, 0.04);
    }

    /* Subtle top/left specular highlight */
    .glass-card-light::before {
      content: '';
      position: absolute;
      inset: 0;
      border-radius: inherit;
      background: linear-gradient(
        135deg,
        rgba(255,255,255,0.2) 0%,
        transparent 50%
      );
      pointer-events: none;
    }

  4.4 FLUTTER IMPLEMENTATION (for mobile app)
  ---------------------------------------------

    class UnjynxGlassCard extends StatelessWidget {
      final Widget child;
      final double opacity;
      final double blurSigma;

      const UnjynxGlassCard({
        required this.child,
        this.opacity = 0.75,
        this.blurSigma = 8.0,
      });

      @override
      Widget build(BuildContext context) {
        final isLight = Theme.of(context).brightness
            == Brightness.light;

        return ClipRRect(
          borderRadius: BorderRadius.circular(16),
          child: BackdropFilter(
            filter: ImageFilter.blur(
              sigmaX: isLight ? 8.0 : 12.0,
              sigmaY: isLight ? 8.0 : 12.0,
            ),
            child: Container(
              decoration: BoxDecoration(
                color: isLight
                  ? const Color(0xFFF8F5FF).withOpacity(0.75)
                  : const Color(0xFF1A0533).withOpacity(0.50),
                borderRadius: BorderRadius.circular(16),
                border: Border.all(
                  color: Colors.white.withOpacity(
                    isLight ? 0.30 : 0.10,
                  ),
                  width: 1.0,
                ),
                boxShadow: isLight
                  ? UnjynxElevation.lightLevel2
                  : null,  // dark uses tonal tint
              ),
              child: child,
            ),
          ),
        );
      }
    }

  4.5 CARD DEFINITION STRATEGIES ON LIGHT BACKGROUNDS
  -----------------------------------------------------

    On dark backgrounds, cards are self-evident -- lighter panels on dark
    ground. On light backgrounds, cards can disappear into the background.
    Three strategies for card definition:

    Strategy A: Shadow-only (Things 3 approach)
    - No visible border, relying entirely on subtle purple-tinted shadow
    - Works when cards have ample margin (16-24px)
    - Feels elegant and minimal
    - Risk: Cards merge in low-contrast environments

    Strategy B: Surface tinting (Linear approach)
    - Cards are a slightly different shade than the background
    - Background: #F8F5FF, Cards: #FFFFFF or #EDE5F7
    - Creates "architectural" hierarchy without shadows
    - Combined with 1px subtle border for extra definition

    Strategy C: Hybrid (Recommended for UNJYNX)
    - Cards use #EDE5F7 (Light Violet) -- slightly cooler than background
    - Very subtle purple shadow (Level 1-2)
    - 1px border at rgba(26,5,51,0.06) -- barely visible, adds definition
    - On hover/press: shadow deepens to Level 2-3
    - Result: Clear hierarchy, brand-consistent, premium feel


################################################################################
  SECTION 5: LIGHT MODE MICRO-INTERACTIONS & ANIMATIONS
################################################################################

  5.1 WHY DARK MODE ANIMATIONS DON'T TRANSLATE TO LIGHT
  -------------------------------------------------------

    The fundamental issue: GLOW EFFECTS ARE INVISIBLE ON LIGHT BACKGROUNDS.
    A gold glow (box-shadow with gold color and blur) that looks stunning on
    #0F0A1A is completely invisible on #F8F5FF. Light emits FROM a light
    surface rather than contrasting against it.

    Motion design in 2026 is "subtle and intentional" -- animations are no
    longer used to impress users but rather to guide attention and confirm
    actions. "Subtlety creates elegance, and the best motion feels like a
    natural extension of the interface, not an animation layered on top."
    Apps with well-executed motion log 15-20% longer sessions according to
    Mixpanel data.

    ANIMATION TRANSLATION TABLE:

    Dark Mode Effect       | Light Mode Alternative
    -----------------------|-----------------------------------------
    Gold glow              | Gold BORDER THICKEN (1px->3px->1px)
    Neon outline           | Saturated border + shadow deepen
    Particle sparkle       | Shimmer sweep (gradient slide)
    Light emission         | Color WASH (bg fills with gold tint)
    Pulse glow             | Scale pulse (1.0->1.02->1.0)
    Trail glow             | After-image shadow (motion blur)
    Ambient glow           | Subtle gradient shift in background
    Confetti (bright)      | Confetti (deeper/muted colors)
    Star burst             | Radial shimmer + scale
    Loading glow ring      | Loading shadow ring (purple shadow)

  5.2 TASK COMPLETION ANIMATION (LIGHT MODE)
  --------------------------------------------

    Dark mode: Gold glow expands from checkbox, brief particle burst.
    Light mode: Different technique needed.

    LIGHT MODE COMPLETION SEQUENCE (350ms total):

    0ms:       Tap checkbox
    0-100ms:   Checkbox fills with #B8860B (Rich Gold)
               Border thickens from 1px to 2px
               Check mark draws (path animation, easeOut)
    100-200ms: Gold WASH radiates outward from checkbox
               Background behind task tints to #FFF8E1
               (Gold Wash) using radial gradient expanding
    200-300ms: Task text gets strikethrough animation
               (line draws left to right at text midpoint)
               Task row subtly compresses (scale Y 1.0->0.98)
    300-350ms: Task slides to completed section
               Gold Wash fades back to normal
    350ms+:    Haptic: medium impact (EFFECT_CLICK)

    The "wash" effect replaces the "glow" effect. Instead of light radiating
    outward (invisible on light bg), COLOR FILLS inward -- the background
    temporarily tints gold, then fades. This creates a satisfying visual
    feedback that works exclusively on light backgrounds.

  5.3 SKELETON LOADING (LIGHT MODE)
  -----------------------------------

    Default skeleton loaders use gray shimmer (Colors.grey[300] ->
    Colors.grey[100]). For UNJYNX light mode, use a LAVENDER SHIMMER:

    UNJYNX Light Skeleton Shimmer:

    Base color:     #EDE5F7  (Light Violet -- matches cards)
    Highlight color: #F8F5FF  (Purple Mist -- matches background)
    Shimmer color:  #FFFFFF   (White peak)

    Shimmer gradient:
    LinearGradient(
      colors: [
        Color(0xFFEDE5F7),  // base
        Color(0xFFF8F5FF),  // mid transition
        Color(0xFFFFFFFF),  // peak highlight
        Color(0xFFF8F5FF),  // mid transition
        Color(0xFFEDE5F7),  // base
      ],
      stops: [0.0, 0.35, 0.5, 0.65, 1.0],
    )

    Duration: 1500ms, repeat
    Direction: left to right

    This creates a branded shimmer that transitions from
    lavender -> purple mist -> white -> purple mist -> lavender.
    It feels premium and distinctly UNJYNX, unlike generic
    gray skeleton loaders used by most apps.

    Flutter implementation: Use the skeletonizer package with custom theme:

    SkeletonizerConfig(
      data: SkeletonizerConfigData(
        effect: ShimmerEffect(
          baseColor: const Color(0xFFEDE5F7),
          highlightColor: const Color(0xFFF8F5FF),
          duration: const Duration(milliseconds: 1500),
        ),
      ),
    )

  5.4 PARTICLE SYSTEMS ON LIGHT BACKGROUNDS
  -------------------------------------------

    On dark backgrounds, particles are bright points of light (gold, white)
    that sparkle against the darkness. On light backgrounds, this approach
    fails -- bright particles blend into the ambient brightness.

    LIGHT MODE PARTICLE RULES:
    - Use FEWER particles (60-70% of dark mode count)
    - Particles should be DARKER (purple tints, gold tints, not white)
    - Reduce particle speed (50-70% of dark mode velocity)
    - Increase particle size slightly (1.5x) to compensate for reduced count
    - Use OPACITY VARIANCE rather than brightness variance
    - Add subtle drop shadows to particles for definition

    Particle colors for light mode celebrations:

    Milestone confetti: #6B21A8 (violet), #B8860B (gold),
                        #059669 (emerald), #1A0533 (midnight)
    Task complete:      No particles (use wash effect instead)
    Level up:           #B8860B (gold) + #6B21A8 (violet)
    Streak milestone:   #B8860B (gold) dominant, 80% of mix

  5.5 SPRING PHYSICS AND MOTION TOKENS
  --------------------------------------

    Motion feels slightly different in light mode. Dark mode animations can
    be more dramatic (larger overshoot, more bounce) because the dark
    environment absorbs excess visual energy. Light mode animations should
    be slightly MORE RESTRAINED:

    Token           | Dark Mode Spring     | Light Mode Spring
    ----------------|----------------------|--------------------
    motionEmphasis  | damping:15, stiff:200| damping:18, stiff:220
    motionDramatic  | damping:12, stiff:150| damping:15, stiff:170
    motionCalm      | 600ms easeInOutCubic | 550ms easeInOutCubic

    Rationale: Higher damping = less overshoot. Light environments make
    motion more visible (less "swallowed" by the background), so slightly
    tighter springs prevent animations from feeling excessive.

    The motion tokens motionQuick (150ms) and motionStandard (250ms)
    remain unchanged between modes -- small, utilitarian animations don't
    need adjustment.

    The ideal micro-interaction duration is between 200 and 500 milliseconds
    -- long enough to be noticed, yet short enough to maintain flow.


################################################################################
  SECTION 6: MATERIAL DESIGN 3 LIGHT THEME BEST PRACTICES
################################################################################

  6.1 TONAL ELEVATION VS SHADOW ELEVATION
  -----------------------------------------

    Material Design 3 moved away from the M2 approach of using only shadows
    for elevation. In M3, elevation is communicated through TONAL SURFACE
    COLORS -- different shades of the surface that indicate different levels
    of hierarchy.

    M3 introduced tone-based surfaces that replace the old opacity-based
    model:
    - surfaceBright
    - surfaceDim
    - surfaceContainerLowest
    - surfaceContainerLow
    - surfaceContainer
    - surfaceContainerHigh
    - surfaceContainerHighest

    For UNJYNX's light mode, this maps to:

    M3 Role                 | UNJYNX Light Token  | Hex
    ------------------------|---------------------|----------
    surface                 | brandPurpleMist     | #F8F5FF
    surfaceContainerLow     | brandSoftLavender   | #F0EAFC
    surfaceContainer        | brandLightViolet    | #EDE5F7
    surfaceContainerHigh    | brandMediumLavender | #E2D9F3
    surfaceContainerHighest | brandDeepLavender   | #D4C8E8
    onSurface               | brandTextPrimary    | #1A0533
    onSurfaceVariant        | brandTextSecondary  | #6B21A8
    primary                 | brandRichGold       | #B8860B
    onPrimary               | white               | #FFFFFF
    inverseSurface          | brandMidnight       | #0F0A1A
    inverseOnSurface        | brandPurpleMist     | #F8F5FF

  6.2 FLUTTER ColorScheme CONFIGURATION
  ---------------------------------------

    UNJYNX should NOT rely solely on ColorScheme.fromSeed() because it
    produces pastel palettes that lack the brand specificity we need.
    Instead, use a HYBRID approach: generate base tonal palette from seed,
    then override specific roles with brand colors.

    The flex_seed_scheme package (by rydmike) provides more control than
    Flutter's built-in fromSeed(). The default tonalSpot variant has pastel
    palettes and won't be too "colorful" even if the seedColor has high
    chroma. For more vibrant results, consider DynamicSchemeVariant.fidelity.

    Implementation:

    import 'package:flex_seed_scheme/flex_seed_scheme.dart';

    final lightColorScheme = SeedColorScheme.fromSeeds(
      brightness: Brightness.light,
      primaryKey: const Color(0xFF6B21A8),  // Violet
      secondaryKey: const Color(0xFFB8860B), // Rich Gold
      tertiaryKey: const Color(0xFF059669),  // Deep Emerald
      tones: FlexTones.material(Brightness.light),
    ).copyWith(
      // Override with exact brand colors
      surface: const Color(0xFFF8F5FF),     // Purple Mist
      onSurface: const Color(0xFF1A0533),   // Midnight Purple
      primary: const Color(0xFFB8860B),     // Rich Gold
      onPrimary: const Color(0xFFFFFFFF),
      secondary: const Color(0xFF6B21A8),   // Violet
      onSecondary: const Color(0xFFFFFFFF),
      error: const Color(0xFFE11D48),       // Deep Rose
      onError: const Color(0xFFFFFFFF),
      surfaceContainerLowest: const Color(0xFFF8F5FF),
      surfaceContainerLow: const Color(0xFFF0EAFC),
      surfaceContainer: const Color(0xFFEDE5F7),
      surfaceContainerHigh: const Color(0xFFE2D9F3),
      surfaceContainerHighest: const Color(0xFFD4C8E8),
    );

  6.3 SURFACE TINT BEHAVIOR IN LIGHT VS DARK
  ---------------------------------------------

    M3's new approach eliminates the old surfaceTintColor overlay (which
    was opacity-based and produced inconsistent results). Instead, the
    tone-based surface colors work differently:

    - Light mode: Higher elevation = slightly MORE saturated/darker surface
      (surfaceContainer -> surfaceContainerHigh -> surfaceContainerHighest)
    - Dark mode: Higher elevation = slightly LIGHTER surface
      (surfaceDim -> surfaceContainer -> surfaceBright)

    This is the OPPOSITE of M2's approach and is more perceptually natural.

    In UNJYNX's light mode:
    - Lowest elements (page bg): lightest purple (#F8F5FF)
    - Cards and containers: slightly more saturated (#EDE5F7)
    - Bottom sheets and dialogs: more saturated still (#E2D9F3)
    - The progression feels like "layers of purple glass stacking up"

  6.4 DYNAMIC COLOR WITH CUSTOM SEED
  ------------------------------------

    ColorScheme.fromSeed(seedColor: Color(0xFF6B21A8)) generates a full
    Material 3 tonal palette from the violet seed. However, the default
    tonalSpot variant produces "pastel palettes" that "won't be too
    colorful even if the seedColor has high chroma."

    For a more vibrant result, consider:
    - DynamicSchemeVariant.fidelity -- preserves more of the seed color's chroma
    - DynamicSchemeVariant.content -- even more faithful to the seed
    - Manual overrides (as shown above) for critical brand colors


