  7.6 COMMON LIGHT MODE FAILURES ACROSS APPS
  ---------------------------------------------

    Through analysis of dozens of productivity apps, recurring failures:

    1. TOO WHITE: Pure #FFFFFF backgrounds feel clinical, sterile. Users
       experience faster eye fatigue. No brand identity.

    2. NO BRAND IDENTITY: Light mode becomes "generic white app." Users
       can't distinguish it from competitors at a glance. The brand
       exists only in dark mode.

    3. GRAY TEXT SYNDROME: Using #9CA3AF or similar medium grays for
       secondary text. These are low personality, low contrast, and feel
       lazy. UNJYNX uses #6B21A8 (violet) for secondary text -- brand
       color IS the hierarchy.

    4. INVISIBLE BORDERS: On white backgrounds, light gray borders (#E5E7EB)
       become nearly invisible. Cards lose definition. UNJYNX uses
       purple-tinted borders (#E2D9F3) that are subtle but visible.

    5. AFTERTHOUGHT ANIMATIONS: Dark mode gets custom glow effects,
       particles, shimmer. Light mode gets... the same thing, which is
       invisible, or nothing at all. Each mode needs its own animation
       language.

    6. INVERTED NOT REDESIGNED: Simply inverting colors produces ugly
       results. "The design needs to really walk in the sun, not just be
       dumped in a bucket of white paint." Every element must be
       reconsidered for light.

    7. NO SHADOW PERSONALITY: Using generic black shadows (#000 at 10%)
       instead of brand-tinted shadows. Looks disjointed on tinted
       backgrounds.


################################################################################
  SECTION 8: TYPOGRAPHY ON LIGHT BACKGROUNDS
################################################################################

  8.1 WHY #1A0533 > #000000 FOR TEXT
  ------------------------------------

    #1A0533 (Midnight Purple) as the primary text color on #F8F5FF achieves
    18.5:1 contrast ratio -- well above WCAG AAA's 7:1 requirement. But the
    more important reason is WARMTH.

    Pure black (#000000) on #F8F5FF:
    - Contrast: ~19.5:1 (slightly higher)
    - Feel: Cold, harsh, disconnected from purple palette
    - The black "sits on top" of the background rather than belonging to it
    - Creates the same halation issue as black-on-white (high luminance delta)

    Midnight Purple (#1A0533) on #F8F5FF:
    - Contrast: ~18.5:1 (still vastly exceeds AAA)
    - Feel: Warm, cohesive, the text BELONGS to the purple ecosystem
    - The slight purple undertone in the text connects it to the background
    - Reduces halation through slightly lower luminance delta
    - Users perceive this as "more readable" even though contrast is
      marginally lower -- perception > mathematics

    The human eye perceives color relationally. When background and text
    share a hue family (purple), the reading experience feels more
    harmonious. This is the Bezold effect -- colors look different depending
    on adjacent colors.

  8.2 FONT WEIGHT ADJUSTMENTS FOR LIGHT MODE
  ---------------------------------------------

    Counterintuitively, text on light backgrounds benefits from SLIGHTLY
    LIGHTER weights than on dark backgrounds. On dark backgrounds, light
    text needs more weight to remain legible (thin strokes get swallowed
    by darkness). On light backgrounds, dark text has inherent high
    contrast, so you can use lighter weights without losing readability.

    UNJYNX Weight Mapping:

    Element          | Dark Mode Weight | Light Mode Weight
    -----------------|------------------|-----------------------
    H1 (Outfit)      | Bold (700)       | SemiBold (600)
    H2 (Outfit)      | SemiBold (600)   | Medium (500)
    H3 (Outfit)      | SemiBold (600)   | Medium (500)
    Body (DM Sans)   | Medium (500)     | Regular (400)
    Caption (DM Sans)| Regular (400)    | Regular (400)
    Stats (Bebas)    | N/A (only one wt)| N/A (only one weight)

    This weight reduction creates a MORE ELEGANT feel in light mode -- the
    text feels airy and editorial rather than heavy and demanding. This is
    why Things 3's light mode feels like "fine stationery" -- they use
    medium weights where others would use bold.

  8.3 ACCENT TEXT COLORS ON WARM BACKGROUNDS
  ---------------------------------------------

    For text that needs to stand out (links, tags, timestamps), use the
    brand violet (#6B21A8) rather than generic blue. This:
    - Maintains brand consistency
    - Achieves good contrast on #F8F5FF (~6.5:1 -- passes AA easily)
    - Feels intentional rather than defaulting to system link color
    - Creates a clear hierarchy: #1A0533 (primary) -> #6B21A8 (secondary)
      -> #475569 (tertiary/metadata)

    For timestamps and low-priority metadata, #475569 (Slate Gray)
    provides 4.8:1 contrast -- the minimum for comfortable reading at
    small sizes (12sp).

  8.4 LINE HEIGHT AND LETTER SPACING
  ------------------------------------

    On light backgrounds with dark text, line height can be slightly more
    generous than on dark backgrounds. The increased ambient brightness
    makes lines feel slightly closer together than they actually are.

    Element     | Dark Line Height | Light Line Height
    ------------|------------------|----------------------------
    H1          | 1.15             | 1.20
    H2          | 1.20             | 1.25
    Body        | 1.50             | 1.55
    Caption     | 1.40             | 1.45

    Letter spacing remains the same between modes -- it is less affected by
    luminance conditions than line height.


################################################################################
  SECTION 9: LIGHT MODE FOR GAMIFICATION ELEMENTS
################################################################################

  9.1 PROGRESS RINGS ON LIGHT BACKGROUNDS
  ------------------------------------------

    UNJYNX's three concentric progress rings (Tasks/Gold, Habits/Violet,
    Focus/Emerald) need adjustment for light mode:

    Dark mode rings:
    - Track (unfilled): 15% white (#FFFFFF26)
    - Fill: vibrant brand colors (#FFD700, #6B21A8, #10B981)
    - Glow effect behind filled portion
    - Completion: ring glows gold for 400ms

    Light mode rings:
    - Track (unfilled): #E2D9F3 (Medium Lavender -- visible but subtle)
    - Fill: deeper brand colors (#B8860B, #6B21A8, #059669)
    - NO glow effect (invisible on light) -- instead use shadow
    - Completion: ring border THICKENS from 6dp to 8dp for 400ms,
      then returns. Subtle scale pulse (1.0->1.03->1.0) with spring.
    - All three complete: simultaneous gold WASH behind the ring area
      (background tints to #FFF8E1 for 1000ms, spring curve)

    Track width adjustment: On light backgrounds, ring tracks should be
    slightly WIDER (8dp vs 6dp in dark mode) because the lower contrast
    makes thin tracks hard to read.

  9.2 XP BARS AND LEVEL INDICATORS
  ----------------------------------

    Duolingo's streak milestones on light backgrounds demonstrate that
    gamification elements can be vibrant on light. Their key technique:
    vibrant colors on a white background with clear containment (rounded
    rect backgrounds, strong borders).

    UNJYNX XP Bar (light mode):

    Container: #EDE5F7 rounded rect (12px radius)
    Track: #E2D9F3 (subtle definition against container)
    Fill: gradient from #B8860B -> #DAA520 (gold gradient)
    Text: "#1A0533" -- current XP / next level
    Milestone markers: small circles at 25%, 50%, 75%
      Unfilled: #D4C8E8
      Filled: #B8860B with 2px white border
    Animation: fill slides with easeOut (250ms)

  9.3 HEATMAP / ACTIVITY GRID ON LIGHT BACKGROUNDS
  ---------------------------------------------------

    The GitHub-style contribution heatmap needs a different color scale for
    light mode. On dark mode, the scale goes from dark (empty) to bright
    (active). On light mode, invert the perception:

    Dark mode scale: #1A0533 -> #3D1F6E -> #6B21A8 -> #9F5FD9 -> #FFD700
    (dark empty -> purple -> bright gold active)

    Light mode scale: #F0EAFC -> #D4C8E8 -> #A78BFA -> #6B21A8 -> #B8860B
    (light lavender empty -> deeper purple -> gold active)

    Level 0 (empty):    #F0EAFC  (Soft Lavender -- barely there)
    Level 1 (low):      #D4C8E8  (Medium Lavender)
    Level 2 (moderate): #A78BFA  (Bright Lavender)
    Level 3 (high):     #6B21A8  (Brand Violet)
    Level 4 (peak):     #B8860B  (Rich Gold -- maximum activity)

    This creates a 5-step lavender -> violet -> gold progression
    that is perceptually uniform, brand-consistent, and accessible
    (each step has measurable contrast difference).

    Research confirms "a simple color scale of 2-3 consecutive hues is good
    to go" for effective data visualization. Our 3-hue system
    (lavender -> purple -> gold) follows this best practice.

  9.4 BADGE AND ACHIEVEMENT CARDS
  ---------------------------------

    On dark backgrounds, badges POP naturally -- metallic gradients, gold
    borders, glowing effects. On light backgrounds, badges need different
    treatment:

    Light Mode Badge Design:
    - Container: #EDE5F7 card with 1px #D4C8E8 border
    - Badge icon: Full-color SVG or Lottie (NOT muted -- badges should be
      the MOST colorful elements on screen)
    - Gold trim: 2px #B8860B border around badge icon area
    - Shadow: Level 2 purple shadow (slightly more prominent than normal)
    - Title text: #1A0533 (bold)
    - Description: #6B21A8 (secondary purple)
    - "Locked" state: Grayscale icon with #E2D9F3 border (no gold trim)
    - Unlock animation: Color sweeps across the badge (grayscale -> color,
      300ms) + gold border draws clockwise (200ms) + scale bounce
      (1.0->1.1->1.0, 350ms spring)

  9.5 STREAK FLAME ON LIGHT BACKGROUNDS
  ----------------------------------------

    Duolingo's streak flame is one of the most recognizable gamification
    elements. On light backgrounds, fire/flame effects actually look MORE
    NATURAL than on dark -- fire exists in daylight all the time. The key
    is color calibration:

    Dark mode flame: Bright orange (#FF6B35) -> yellow (#FFD700) -> white core
    Light mode flame: Deep orange (#D4540F) -> gold (#B8860B) -> warm yellow
    (#DAA520) core

    The light mode flame should be RICHER and DEEPER in color (not washed
    out). Reduce any "white hot" center to a warm yellow instead.

    Use Lottie for the animated flame (typically 5-50KB compressed).
    Create TWO Lottie variants -- one for each mode -- with different color
    palettes. Do NOT try to CSS-filter or color-shift a single animation.

    Duolingo's approach: Previous streak milestones featured "Duo holding
    number balloons, which was cute but not quite celebratory enough in
    terms of energy." They evolved to phoenix imagery with much more
    exciting and powerful animations. UNJYNX should follow this principle --
    milestones should feel powerful, not cute.


################################################################################
  SECTION 10: LIGHT MODE ACCESSIBILITY
################################################################################

  10.1 CONTRAST REQUIREMENTS SUMMARY
  ------------------------------------

    UNJYNX targets WCAG 2.2 Level AA with AAA where achievable.

    Element           | Required | UNJYNX (Light) | Status
    ------------------|----------|----------------|-------------------
    Primary text      | 4.5:1    | 18.5:1         | AAA (exceptional)
    Secondary text    | 4.5:1    | ~6.5:1         | AA
    Tertiary text     | 4.5:1    | ~4.8:1         | AA
    Large headings    | 3:1      | 18.5:1         | AAA
    Gold CTA button   | 3:1      | 4.8:1          | AA
    Gold CTA text     | 4.5:1    | white on gold  | Need to verify
    Success green     | 3:1      | ~5.2:1         | AA
    Warning amber     | 3:1      | ~4.1:1         | AA (borderline)
    Error red         | 3:1      | ~5.8:1         | AA
    Borders           | 3:1      | ~3.2:1         | AA (meets min)
    Focus indicator   | 3:1      | see below      | Designed for AA
    Disabled text     | N/A      | ~2.5:1         | Exempt (by design)

    Note on white text on gold (#B8860B) CTA buttons:
    White (#FFFFFF) on #B8860B = approximately 4.5:1 -- just meets AA for
    normal text. For critical CTAs, consider using #FFFFFF in bold or
    at 16sp+ to ensure comfortable readability. Alternative: use #1A0533
    (midnight purple) text on gold for 4.2:1 -- works for large text (18sp+).

  10.2 FOCUS INDICATORS
  ----------------------

    WCAG 2.2 introduced SC 2.4.11 (Focus Not Obscured), SC 2.4.12 (Focus
    Not Obscured Enhanced), and SC 2.4.13 (Focus Appearance). Focus
    indicators must be at least 2px thick, cover significant area, and have
    3:1 contrast against surrounding colors.

    UNJYNX Light Mode Focus Indicator:

    Default (keyboard navigation):
    - outline: 2px solid #6B21A8 (Violet -- 6.5:1 on #F8F5FF)
    - outline-offset: 2px (separation from element edge)
    - border-radius: inherit (matches element shape)

    High-contrast (for inputs, buttons):
    - outline: 3px solid #1A0533 (Midnight -- 18.5:1)
    - outline-offset: 2px

    Flutter:
    focusColor: Color(0xFF6B21A8).withOpacity(0.3),
    // Violet tint behind focused element

    For custom widgets, use :focus-visible equivalent:
    Wrap with Focus widget + custom border on isFocused

    Important: Default browser focus indicators are exempt from contrast
    requirements, but once you override styles, YOU are responsible for
    meeting 3:1 minimum. UNJYNX overrides all focus styles, so all custom
    indicators must meet requirements.

  10.3 COLOR-BLIND SAFE CONSIDERATIONS
  --------------------------------------

    ~5% of the global population has color vision deficiency, predominantly
    red-green (deuteranopia/protanopia). UNJYNX's color palette was analyzed:

    SAFE combinations:
    - Purple (#6B21A8) + Gold (#B8860B): SAFE -- different hue families
    - Purple (#6B21A8) + Emerald (#059669): SAFE -- distinct even in
      deuteranopia simulation
    - Gold (#B8860B) + Error Red (#E11D48): CAUTION -- can appear similar
      in protanopia

    MITIGATIONS:
    - Never rely on color ALONE to convey information
    - Always pair color with: icon, text label, pattern, or position
    - Priority indicators: use icons (flag shapes) not just color
    - Success/error: always include checkmark/X icon + text
    - Heatmap: add numerical labels or tooltip on hover/tap
    - Progress rings: each ring has a DIFFERENT pattern (solid, dashed, dotted)
      as accessibility option

    Purple + Gold specifically:
    "Pink-turquoise-grey and purple-blue are problematic color combinations
    for red and green color weak/blind people." However, purple + gold
    (orange family) is SAFE because gold is perceived differently from
    purple across all common color vision deficiencies.

    Blue colors are the safest bet for universal perception. Gold (as an
    orange-family color) is also universally well-perceived. Purple sits
    in the blue-red spectrum, which can be problematic when paired with
    blue -- but purple + gold avoids this entirely.

  10.4 REDUCED MOTION AND ACCESSIBILITY SETTINGS
  ------------------------------------------------

    For users with vestibular disorders or motion sensitivity:

    When MediaQuery.of(context).disableAnimations is true:
    - All spring physics -> instant transitions
    - Shimmer loading -> static skeleton (solid #EDE5F7 shapes)
    - Completion wash -> instant checkbox fill (no radial expansion)
    - Particle effects -> disabled entirely
    - Page transitions -> simple fade (200ms)
    - Streak flame -> static icon (no animation)

    When MediaQuery.of(context).boldText is true:
    - All font weights increase by one step (400->500, 500->600, 600->700)
    - The light mode weight reduction (Section 8.2) is REVERSED

    When MediaQuery.of(context).highContrast is true:
    - Surface colors flatten to fewer levels (only 2: bg + card)
    - Borders thicken to 2px and darken to #1A0533 at 30%
    - Text colors simplify to only #1A0533 (no secondary/tertiary)
    - Shadows deepen by 50% (alpha values increase)

  10.5 EUROPEAN ACCESSIBILITY ACT (JUNE 2025)
  ---------------------------------------------

    The European Accessibility Act became legally binding as of June 28, 2025.
    This makes WCAG conformance not just a best practice but a legal
    requirement for products serving European users. UNJYNX must ensure:
    - All interactive elements have 3:1+ contrast
    - All text has 4.5:1+ contrast (7:1+ for AAA)
    - Focus indicators are visible and meet SC 2.4.11-13
    - Color is not the sole means of conveying information
    - All animations can be disabled


